<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 92 / BMA hits at central elements of reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British Medical Association yesterday rejected the central elements of
the government's health reforms at a conference which its leaders had
struggled to prevent becoming party-political.
Ministers have claimed the reforms, a year old next week, are beginning to
win the support of the medical profession.
Some BMA members believed that yesterday's conference, arranged before the
election was called to discuss the health reforms and a programme for
improving health standards in the 1990s, should not have taken place at such
a politically sensitive time. But a bid to adjourn it received little
support.
The BMA is politically neutral, but while overtly party-political points
were avoided during the conference, the debate revealed continuing hostility
and suspicion among doctors. This will be welcomed by Labour as it maintains
efforts to keep health at the forefront of the campaign.
The conference adopted resolutions which:
warned that widespread GP fundholding would lead to 'fragmented funding,
progressive operational instability and no base for strategic and capital
planning';
said that the government's internal market would jeopardise the training of
junior doctors;
declared that no further trust hospitals should be established until the
first and second waves had been 'fully evaluated over an adequate period of
time and found to enhance patient care'.
A motion which sought to give BMA support to separating the purchasing of
health care from its provision - the central aim of the reforms  - was
defeated.
The three main political parties all favour versions of the
purchaser-provider split, and BMA leaders clearly expected this to be a less
controversial issue. Dr Jeremy Lee-Potter, BMA council chairman, said many
people now believed that the 'centralised command economy' of the old-style
National Health Service was unsuitable.
But Sir Anthony Grabham, one of the BMA's most distinguished council
members, said doctors were now 'in an inappropriate commercial competition'.
</TEXT>
