<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 92 / International Company News: Probe will not hold up Nestle
bid for Perrier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE, the Swiss food group bidding for Perrier, made clear yesterday it
would not be prevented from buying shares in the French mineral water group
during the European Commission's four-month investigation into the bid.
The Swiss company expects to launch its FFr15.46bn (Dollars 2.76bn) bid
officially in the next few days. Technically, the merger will be suspended
during the EC's investigation, announced two days ago, but Nestle is allowed
to go ahead with the public offer.
Under EC rules, the group will be unable to exercise the voting rights
attached to any Perrier shares it buys, except to 'maintain the full value'
of its investment.
If the Commission decides the bid is anti-competitive, it can ask Nestle to
unwind the merger. However, it seems more likely that Brussels will try to
amend the deal - for example, by asking Nestle to sell some mineral water
brands.
Since new rules came into force in September 1990, the Commission has only
once outlawed a merger - the Franco-Italian bid for de Havilland, the
Canadian aircraft maker - and has never quashed a public offer.
</TEXT>
