FT  27 MAR 92 / International Company News: Varity slides into red on
USDollars 108m charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VARITY, the international farm and industrial machinery group, suffered a 12
per cent drop in sales last year. After a special USDollars 108m
restructuring charge, it posted a net loss of Dollars 178m, or Dollars 7.87
a share. This compares with a profit of Dollars 94.4m, or Dollars 2.77 a
share, in fiscal 1991.
Varity's biggest markets were hit by the recession. Overall sales were
Dollars 3.2bn for the year ended January 31 1992, against Dollars 3.6bn in
fiscal 1991. Farm equipment sales were down 19 per cent and diesel engine
sales fell 15 per cent.
Vehicle components, accounting for nearly half the business, dipped 7 per
cent.
In the final quarter, after the restructuring charge, Varity's loss was
Dollars 115.3m, or Dollars 4.80, against net profit of Dollars 19.1m, or 56
cents. Sales were Dollars 899m, against Dollars 896m.
Mr Victor Rice, chairman, said Varity's restructuring was aimed at improving
operating performance in fiscal 1993 'whether or not there is an economic
recovery'. Worldwide payroll will be cut by 1,300, or 7 per cent, to lower
operating costs by Dollars 45m. Varity has reduced manpower by nearly 3,000
already since 1989.
The job cuts will take Dollars 40m of the special charge, while Dollars 68m
comprises non-cash writedowns for future asset sales. Over the next 18
months, Varity hopes to raise up to Dollars 175m from asset sales, to be
applied to debt.
Varity sees moderate improvement in some sectors this year, and overall
operating results should be substantially better.
The Kelsey-Hayes vehicle component subsidiary had operating income of
Dollars 106m in fiscal 1992, against Dollars 135m.
Perkins was badly hit by the UK recession and operating income was Dollars
35m, against Dollars 61m. Demand will continue to be sluggish, but Perkins
will benefit from a 10-year engine supply pact with Caterpillar of the US,
worth an estimated Dollars 1bn.
</TEXT>
