<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAR 92 / The Lex Column: United Newspapers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Thanks partly to higher circulation at the Sunday Express, United Newspapers
looks well placed for economic recovery. Pre-tax profit of Pounds 85m was at
the top end of expectations. The dividend is well covered. Interest cover is
over three times, including payments on the preference shares. Capital
spending will rise by Pounds 19m this year, but there would still be scope
to maintain the dividend without higher borrowing. Recovery should boost
advertising, though it might be 1993 before this feeds through to the
lucrative classified sector.
Were this the whole story, a yield of 7.5 per cent would leave the shares
attractive even after yesterday's rise of nearly 4 per cent. The trouble is
that prospects would look different if recovery were thwarted by higher
interest rates after the election. No surprise, then, that the Daily Express
is working so hard for the Tories.
</TEXT>
