FT  27 MAR 92 / World Trade News: Electronics companies deny infringement of
US patents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE electronics companies yesterday denied they had violated patents
related to charge coupled devices - a basic component of video cameras and
photocopy machines - held by Loral Fairchild, subsidiary of the US defence
electronics company Loral.
Loral has brought a suit in the US against a range of Japanese and Korean
companies, including market leaders such as Sony, Matsushita and Canon, over
alleged patent infringements. Loral is claiming billions of dollars in
damages.
Charge coupled devices (CCDs) are electronic eyes that sense visual images
and translate them into electronic signals.
The suit is reminiscent of a recent action by Honeywell of the US against
Minolta, the camera-maker, over auto-focus cameras which led to an
out-of-court settlement for Dollars 127.5m after the court ruled against
Minolta. Honeywell has also filed suits against other camera makers.
The Japanese companies appeared unclear yesterday precisely why Loral
Fairchild believed its patents had been infringed. They said the technology
for CCDs was based on licences from American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, and said
they had no case to answer.
</TEXT>
