<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Housing figures give Dow only
brief boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
FURTHER signs of recovery in the housing market helped provide a boost to US
stock markets early yesterday, but a rush of late sellers left leading
indices slightly lower at the end of trading, writes Patrick Harverson in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was finally 1.57 off at 3,259.39 after
waves of selling in the final half-hour had wiped 14 points off the index.
The Standard &amp; Poor's 500, moving in similar fashion, lost 1.36 at 407.52,
while the Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks ended just 0.80 up at
619.48. New York SE turnover came to 192.6m shares.
Although prices opened weaker, the market judged the morning's economic data
as a positive influence on sentiment and by late morning the leading indices
had moved into the black. The clear good news was the 9.3 per cent rise in
February existing home sales.
The 0.1 per cent decline in February durable goods orders was disappointing,
although a closer examination showed that non-defence orders rose for the
third successive month, which some analysts said was evidence of a revival
in the industrial sector.
Airlines remained under pressure after Tuesday's heavy profit-taking. Delta
was hardest hit, with trading delayed due to an order imbalance on the sell
side as the second analyst in two days lowered his earnings estimate on
concern about falling passenger-mile yields. When business resumed, Delta
fell Dollars 1 to Dollars 63 3/4 .
Federated Department Stores, the retailing group which emerged from
bankruptcy last month, moved forward Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 15 3/8 after
County NatWest upgraded its rating from a 'hold' to an 'accumulate'. On
Tuesday, Federated said it would soon launch its computerised inventory
system to improve co-ordination between suppliers and vendors.
Commodore International jumped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 14 3/8 after the
company was cleared of any tax liability under a settlement with the
Internal Revenue Service on all major issues relating to Commodore's tax
litigation between 1981 and 1986.
On the Nasdaq, Microsoft rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 128 1/2 in the wake of
its acquisition of Fox Software.
American Mobile Systems dropped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 4 5/8 after its
president was said to have been suspended and an investigation opened into
the unauthorised transfer of Dollars 4.1m out of company accounts.
Canada
BANK AND real estate issues rebounded as the Toronto market began shaking
off nervousness over Olympia &amp; York's financial difficulties, and gold
shares rallied from recent weakness.
The composite index picked up 14.5 to 3,452.3 and rises led falls by 318 to
244 after volume of 35.1m shares.
</TEXT>
