<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: US ruling permits logging in
endangered owl forests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Supreme Court yesterday gave victory to the US timber industry in yet
another round of its protracted battle with environmentalists concerning the
protection of the Northern Spotted Owl and the forests inhabited by the
endangered bird in the Pacific Northwest.
The court revived a 1989 federal law which barred environmental lawsuits
against logging in old-growth forests in Washington and Oregon states. The
1989 law, supported by the Bush administration in an effort to protect
timber industry jobs, had been struck down in 1990 as unconstitutional by
the ninth circuit court of appeals in San Francisco.
Yesterday's ruling may permit some 16 blocked timber sales, worth Dollars
30m (Pounds 17.3m). It will have limited impact on the issue of protecting
the owl, as the 1989 bill was due to expire.
Bush administration officials said yesterday they would issue a preservation
plan for the spotted owl in April. They were responding to criticism from
Democratic congressmen who told a House hearing that the White House had
blatantly ignored laws to preserve the owl. Meanwhile, Mr Cy Jamison,
director of the Bureau of Land Management, which controls large tracts of
forest in Oregon, said his agency would run out of marketable timber in the
west of the state by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
