<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / International Capital Markets: GE cuts investment in Hungary
operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Electric of the US is retrenching at its Tungsram light bulb
operation in Hungary, one of the earliest and largest joint ventures by a
western company in eastern Europe.
GE announced cuts in investment, employment and production at Tungsram after
preliminary results showed the subsidiary had lost Ft1.1bn (Dollars 13.6m)
last year.
Up to half of the planned investment of Dollars 40m for 1992 is to be held
back. Staffing levels are to be reduced 25 per cent, with administrators
most sharply hit. Production facilities will be idled for an average of two
weeks to allow a reduction of stocks.
Only last June,GE increased its stake in Tungsram to more than 75 per cent
and took total investment to more than Dollars 200m, declaring confidence in
the subsidiary's prospects.
GE-Tungsram blamed rising local costs for the reversal and called for
devaluation of the forint, the Hungarian currency, to keep pace with
inflation. The company said that a 40 per cent gap between inflation and
currency depreciation had put the survival of Hungarian exporters into
question.
At the same time, prices for lighting products in Tungsram's main west
European markets are falling.
Mr Gyorgy Varga, chief executive of GE-Tungsram, said that Suzuki, Ford and
General Motors, which are all embarking on large investments in Hungary,
would face similar problems.
GE has been frustrated in repeated efforts to force a change in
exchange-rate policy. The Hungarian government, bound by its agreement with
the International Monetary Fund, remains commited to a policy of firm
monetary policy and high exchange rates to maintain downward pressure on
inflation, even if that is painful for exporters.
Nevertheless, GE maintained that Tungsram's long-term promise remained
bright.
</TEXT>
