<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / International Company News: P&amp;G plans to divest its pulp
interests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROCTER &amp; Gamble, the US consumer products giant, yesterday took a step away
from vertical industrial integration when it announced it was putting up for
sale its large interests in the pulp business.
The company has retained Goldman Sachs, the New York investment bank, to
find buyers for the business, which employs 3,200 people and is expected to
have sales in 1992 of around Dollars 800m.
About half of its output is sold to Procter &amp; Gamble itself for use in a
variety of products. However, Mr Edwin Artzt, P&amp;G's chairman, said a review
of corporate goals into the next century had concluded that the commercial
pulp business was not 'a good fit with P&amp;G's long-term strategic interests'.
He said the group's aim was to be 'more globally focused on our core
consumer businesses in healthcare, beauty care, laundry and cleaning
products, paper products and food and beverages'.
He added that the decision did not mean that P&amp;G would eliminate all
internal vertical integration of raw materials. These decisions were to be
made on a case-by-case basis.
P&amp;G has been in the pulp business for 70 years and its operations include a
cotton linters pulp plant in Memphis, Tennessee, and wood pulp plants in
Oglethorpe, Georgia, Perry, Florida, and Grande Prairie, Alberta. It also
has timber assets in Georgia and Florida and sawmills in Georgia and
Alberta.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the credit rating agency, affirmed the company's Double-A
senior debt rating in the wake of the announcement. It said the proceeds of
the sale were likely to be used to fund P&amp;G's international diversification,
so total debt was unlikely to be reduced significantly.
Mr Artzt said the company had analysed the benefits of vertical integration
and had concluded that it would be better off working with raw materials
suppliers than producing materials internally.
</TEXT>
