<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Democrat race intensifies as Clinton attacks Brown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bill Clinton, stung by defeat in Tuesday's Democratic presidential
primary in Connecticut, yesterday gave up trying to ignore Mr Jerry Brown.
The front-runner for the party nomination described the policies of his
conqueror, a former governor of California, as typical of a 'charter member
of the flat earth society'.
He told a news conference in New York, scene of the next big primary two
weeks from now, that Mr Brown's proposed flat rate of income and value-added
taxes would be 'a disaster - a war-on-New York tax'. It would, he said,
'triple taxes on the poor, increase taxes on the middle class by an average
Dollars 1,900 a year, and lower taxes on rich Americans'.
But Mr Brown immediately flew in the afternoon to Albany, capital of New
York state, to meet the state's most powerful politician, Governor Mario
Cuomo, who is barely on speaking terms with Mr Clinton after the latter had
suggested he might have Mafia connections.
The Californian was only given ten minutes with the governor and received no
endorsement. Asked if he agreed with Mr Brown that Mr Clinton would be 'the
ruin of the Democratic party', Mr Cuomo merely replied he would only say
such a thing if he were running himself.
But, thickening the plot, a leader of the 'draft Cuomo' movement in New York
said that, if Democrats there really wanted their governor to run for
president, then a vote for Mr Brown would best serve that end.
The tendency of the Democratic party's national leaders yesterday was to
rally behind Mr Clinton, largely because Mr Brown is seen as unelectable in
November.
Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa, an earlier candidate for the Democratic
nomination, was meeting Mr Clinton last night with a view to an endorsement
today. His union backing may help blunt Mr Brown's appeal to organised
labour.
Mr Ron Brown, party chairman, pointed out that Mr Clinton still had an
enormous lead in delegates won.
But defeat in New York and in Wisconsin, which also holds its primary on
April 7, would encourage the search for an alternative candidate, though it
would not necessarily produce one.
On Tuesday, Mr Brown narrowly beat Mr Clinton, governor of Arkansas, by
37-36 per cent, with Mr Paul Tsongas, who pulled out of the race last week
but remained on the ballot, scoring 20 per cent. Even so, the rules meant
that Mr Clinton won more delegates to the party nominating convention in
July, with 22 against Mr Brown's 21, and ten for Mr Tsongas.
On the Republican side, President George Bush again was embarrassed by a
one-third vote against his candidacy, even though he had little formal
opposition. Mr Pat Buchanan won 22 per cent, uncommitted delegates took 9
per cent and the Louisiana rightwinger Mr David Duke 2 per cent.
Disenchanted Democrats, Page 7
</TEXT>
