<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Observer: Futuristic
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The New York Commodity Exchange, with a reputation more for slumped volumes
than for innovation, has elected a woman as its new chairman, the first to
head a US futures market.
Donna Redel, no back-office type, apparently more than holds her own in the
rough and tumble of the pits - earning a rebuke from the exchange some years
ago for duffing up a man trader who shoved her the wrong way.
She also has connections. Executive vice-president of family firm Redel
Trading, she is the daughter of Comex ex-chairman Irving Redel.
Her affinities are more akin to the large brokerage houses, and she won
yesterday against Sidney Rothberg who reflects the interests of the
independent traders.
She will be hard put to win new business for the fading exchange. Its volume
as the main US metals-trading market has been falling. Nor has Comex been
able to develop new attractive products.
Plenty of politicking is assured with yet another attempt at rapprochement
between rival exchanges. Four out of five New York futures markets plan a
costly move to a new trading floor and pos-sible merger. For her efforts,
she will be Comex's first paid chairman at Dollars 125,000 a year.
</TEXT>
