<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Worker qualification standards criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW BRITISH qualifications have led to young people being taught how to lay
bricks but not how to estimate the materials required, according to a study
published yesterday by the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research.
The study, by Ms Hilary Steedman, compares young people on construction
industry courses in France and Germany, and says the British teenager on a
Youth Training (YT) programme is 'uniquely disadvantaged in northern
Europe'.
It finds that the new British competence-based National Vocational
Qualification (NVQ) for the industry has less mathematics training than the
City and Guilds qualification. Numbers of people attaining a recognised NVQ
would rise, but the quality of those trained might be lower than before.
The vocational qualification is based on standards of competence elaborated
by the industry as appropriate for an employee at this level.
The report said: 'It is difficult to understand, therefore, that so little
emphasis should be placed in the industry on building calculations.'
It said shifting the financial burden for training away from government and
towards employers was a reason for the reduction in education and training
in YT.
Mathematics in Vocational Youth Training for the Building Trades in Britain,
France and Germany. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench Street, Smith Square, London SW1P
3HE. Pounds 3.
</TEXT>
