<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Print employers warn over hung parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRINT EMPLOYERS warned yesterday of the dangers to business confidence of a
hung parliament as it emerged that more than a third of them expect to cut
jobs in the next three months.
The British Printing Industries Federation said that, with an election out
of the way business confidence would revive, but it added that that assumed
that the outcome was not a hung parliament.
Its comments reflect concern among the business community that an election
with no clear winner would lead to uncertainty among customers and a longer
recession.
The federation said its quarterly survey of companies with sales of Pounds
1.2bn had produced mixed results.
Members reported that the first quarter of this year, which they had assumed
would be tough, was far worse than expected. Some 94 per cent of companies
were working below capacity. Eight out of 10 had reduced employment, whereas
only four out of 10 had expected to do so.
Employment prospects remain bleak, with 36 per cent planning further job
losses in the next quarter.
Smaller companies often shed staff by non-replacement but job shedding at
larger companies is more likely to involve redundancies. The federation
added that encouragement could be taken from the fact that two thirds of
companies believed the next three months would see an improvement in the
industry's fortunes.
Not since April 1987 has such a large proportion looked forward to better
times. Even so, the federation said most members believed it would be the
autumn before a real, as opposed to a seasonal, upturn was evident.
Hopes for stable prices have faded. Almost three in five companies have cut
prices recently, compared with the forecast one in 10. Some 20 per cent plan
further reductions.
</TEXT>
