<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Falling trend shown in home repossessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORTGAGE repossession orders issued by courts last month were down by nearly
a quarter on their peak monthly levels last year.
The figures, published by the Lord Chancellor's Department, were welcomed by
the Council of Mortgage Lenders which said they showed a clearly declining
trend in the number of people losing their homes because they were unable to
keep up mortgage payments.
The figures from the Lord Chancellor's Department show that in February
lenders made 12,889 applications for repossession orders and 4,752 orders
were issued. That compares with 13,453 applications and 5,408 orders in
January.
The January and February totals were well below those recorded between April
and October last year. Repossessions peaked in July when there were almost
17,000 applications for eviction and 6,951 orders. About 75,500 people were
evicted last year for failing to keep up mortgage payments. At the end of
last year, 275,000 borrowers were six months or more in arrears and in
danger of eviction.
Last December the government and main mortgage lenders prepared measures
intended to prevent a possible flood of repossessions.
Mr Mark Boleat, CML director-general, yesterday warned that the Lord
Chancellor's figures were a very inexact indicator of repossessions but said
they suggested that, along with lower interest rates, the rescue measures
were assisting the situation.
</TEXT>
