<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Agency set up to run Rover marketing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROVER GROUP announced plans yesterday for a marketing strategy that might
spearhead a radical overhaul of the way UK companies use advertising
agencies.
Almost all Rover's marketing services will be handled by an agency set up to
promote the motor manufacturer.
The company said its decision to jettison about 30 different marketing and
advertising agencies in favour of one agency was driven by the need for an
integrated service. It would result in savings of perhaps 10 per cent of
Rover's marketing budget, which is about Pounds 100m a year.
The move to put Rover's marketing services in the hands of one agency has
caused ripples throughout advertising. The BSB agency, part of the Saatchi
group, was Rover's main agency and will lose revenue of Pounds 20m a year,
keeping only Land Rover UK's advertising for the time being.
Mr Kevin Morley, managing director of Rover Marketing and a long-standing
group executive, was named yesterday as chairman of the agency - the Kevin
Morley Group (KMG). He will retain his non-executive membership of the Rover
board.
Rover's decision to contract out its marketing and advertising to a former
employee follows a move in January this year, when Mr Royden Axe, a leading
designer, retired from Rover to start his own design company - Design
Research Associates (DRA). Rover is one of DRA's main clients.
The first advertisements of a campaign for the Metro range were launched
yesterday.
KMG - which has a five-year contract with Rover - will soon announce new
business apart from Rover.
The advertising industry is anxious that, should KMG prove successful with
Rover, other large advertisers might follow suit and demand cheaper
marketing services.
Marketing, Page 23; Observer, Page 27
</TEXT>
