<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Main parties all seek changes in accountancy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL THREE main parties would consider changes to the structure and operation
of accountancy after the election, it emerged yesterday.
Mr John Redwood, the minister for corporate affairs, said he would
contemplate 'tip-off' legislation to encourage auditors to inform regulators
of any fraud if the existing voluntary arrangements were judged to be
failing.
He said it was too early to assess whether the self-regulatory mechanisms
for auditors set up late last year would work. He said he had no reason to
believe they would fail, but did not rule out more direct parliamentary
intervention if they were not effective.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour's official voice on the City, said she wanted to
review the legal definition of fraud.
She is also considering requiring auditors to comment publicly on the
quality of a company's internal controls, and for compulsory audit
committees filled with non-executive directors.
She ruled out any requirements for auditors to a company to be 'rotated'
periodically, or to prevent them carrying out other work for their audit
clients. She said that would reduce the profession's ability to attract
high-quality recruits and might harm its competitive advantage in Europe.
However, she said she would consider a requirement for partners working on
any one audit client to be changed periodically to bring a fresh perspective
to the job.
Mr Alex Carlisle, trade and industry spokesman for the Liberal Democrats,
said he would support an Office of Fair Trading investigation of the
profession.
He said the recent mergers between firms had reduced the number too far, and
suggested that liability cases threatened the survival of those which
remained. 'Accountancy is now concentrated in far too few hands,' he said.
He also said the law governing auditors' liability in detecting fraud should
be reviewed.
Accountants challenged to vote wisely, Page 17
</TEXT>
