<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Yeltsin pressed to quit as PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICAL pressure is mounting in Moscow to remove Mr Boris Yeltsin as prime
minister and install an administration less committed to radical economic
reform.
Mr Yeltsin, who is both president and prime minister, remains Russia's most
popular politician, but has been identified with his government's severe
economic reforms and made vulnerable to parliamentary attack.
The first strong signs of the political offensive against him emerged this
week. Tuesday's meeting of the Constitutional Commission cut the
parliamentary votes needed to remove a prime minister from two-thirds to a
bare majority and deleted Mr Yeltsin's right to appoint regional governors.
Mr Yeltsin may be able to restore the lost clauses but the anti-government
victory shows the rising tide of discontent.
The opposition is centred among disaffected deputies who are unhappy with Mr
Yeltsin's concentration of powers. Earlier this month, Mr Yeltsin added the
post of defence minister to his portfolios. Under his presidency, Russia has
assumed most of the powers of the former Soviet Union. Last October he also
won the right to legislate by decree - a right deputies now regret.
Mr Yeltsin admitted yesterday that the government would fall if he were
replaced as prime minister, because it depends on his popularity. No one
will challenge him as president, but many deputies feel he should go as
premier.
Some observers believe he will have to sacrifice Mr Genady Burbulis, the
unpopular first deputy prime minister, although he may be able to defend Mr
Yegor Gaidar, the deputy prime minister in charge of economic reform.
A western diplomat said yesterday: 'Gaidar is very important for the IMF
right now, and Yeltsin knows how important the IMF is to him.'
G7 aid to Russia, Page 2
Oil price to rise, Page 40
