<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Call for pension control changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS would be prevented from using pension fund surpluses for their own
purposes under pensions law proposals being urged by the Institute for
Policy Research, the left-of-centre think tank. It also proposes giving
control over funds to beneficiaries.
The report addresses the most sensitive question being considered by
legislators considering pensions law: whether a pension fund surplus is the
property of the employer or of the scheme's members.
The institute rejects employers' arguments that liability to make good any
deficit entitles them to recoup surpluses. Although employers are correct in
theory, the report notes that most scheme rules give employers the right to
cease their contributions at any time, regardless of the financial state of
the pension fund.
Provisions in the 1990 Social Security Act which will require employers to
make good deficiencies when a pension fund is wound up may be ineffective
because a financially troubled employer may simply stop contributing and not
wind the fund up until the options run out - upon bankruptcy. The report
suggests that in return for surrendering their right to use surpluses,
employers' contributions should be defined and limited.
Employer and employee contributions should be a contractually binding matter
to be renegotiated periodically. Contributions levels in the event of a
surplus or deficit would be spelled out. Making up shortfalls would be a
matter to be negotiated between employers and beneficiaries.
Locking the Stable Door, Institute of Public Policy Research, 30-32
Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
