<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brazil to state coffee pact
stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRAZILIAN government is expected to make an official statement today to
reveal a position favourable to the establishment of quotas by exporting
countries in the negotiations on the International Coffee Agreement, which
begin in London on April 6.
Mr Oswaldo Aranha Neto, president of the Brazilian Federation of Coffee
Exporters (Febec) confirmed that 'a clear consensus exists' to back economic
clauses based on quotas. Febec had originally favoured a buffer stock scheme
instead of quotas. The National Coffee Council, a producers group, had been
lobbying hard for a return to a quota system.
Officials in both the economy ministry and the foreign ministry continue to
refuse to comment about the likely Brazilian position. Mr Francisco Rezek,
the foreign minister, is reported to have discussed the Brazilian position
in the negotiations with President Fernando Collor de Mello at a meeting
yesterday.
London traders said coffee prices reached the day's highs on news that the
Brazilian government was set to announce its official position on the coffee
pact, reports Reuter.
But prices soon drifted lower again, with May closing Dollars 1 down at
Dollars 873 a tonne. In the morning it touched a low of Dollars 866 a tone.
'The market is not taking seriously anymore these comments that are coming
out of producing countries,' said one trader.
</TEXT>
