<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / International Company News: Nestle's bid for Perrier
suspended for EC inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE'S FFr15.46bn (Dollars 2.74bn) bid for Perrier was suspended for a
further four months yesterday when the European Commission announced it
would launch an investigation into the deal's impact on the French mineral
water market.
The Swiss food group only overcame the opposition of the Agnelli family to
its offer two days ago. But the Commission said yesterday that, following
its one-month automatic inquiry into the bid, it had decided there were
serious doubts about the takeover's compatibility with the European market.
Competition officials said the decision to move to a full investigation took
into account Nestle's pledge to sell Volvic, one of the Perrier waters, to
BSN, the food group. If the Commission decides the bid is anti-competitive
it could ask Nestle to unwind the merger or amend it, for example, by
selling some Perrier brands.
Nestle and its allies had already anticipated the EC inquiry. Earlier this
week, Mr Reto Domeniconi, Nestle's director-general, told a press conference
in Paris he thought it probable that the commission would opt for an
in-depth investigation given the 'complexity' of the affair.
The inquiry will hinge on the comparative shares of the French mineral water
market held by Nestle/Perrier after the bid. Nestle, which would be adding
the eponymous Perrier and several smaller brands to Vittel, which it owns,
estimates its eventual share at 41 per cent in volume.
The Commission says that in the overall French market for bottled water, and
separate segments - such as still or sparkling water - the merged company
will have a share of more than 50 per cent.
Meanwhile, BSN is expected to increase its share of the same market to 32
per cent. Apart from Volvic - promised to BSN as the price for alliance with
Nestle in the Perrier battle - the group's other waters include Evian and
Badoit.
Lex, Page 28
</TEXT>
