<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Clifford pins hopes on Japanese crumbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLIFFORD FOODS, the dairy products and fruit juice company, yesterday
reported a 20 per cent fall in profits but said it had high hopes for
Japanese crumbs.
The company has spent Pounds 2.5m, including ovens imported from Japan, to
make breadcrumbs to sell to makers of breaded poultry and fish.
Mr Brian Lambe, finance director, said Japanese crumbs were better quality
and generated higher margins. 'They tend to be splintery type crumbs rather
than ball crumbs,' he added.
Clifford announced pre-tax profits down from Pounds 6.65m to Pounds 5.3m in
the year to December 31. This was due to price cutting among companies
supplying milk to supermarkets, an activity which generates about 27 per
cent of Clifford's turnover.
Price cutting by competitors lost Clifford margin and business, although
some custom has since been recovered. The company is also talking to
customers about a price rise in a bid to restore margins to levels of a year
ago.
Turnover fell 5 per cent to Pounds 140.6m. Interest charges were lower at
Pounds 655,000 (Pounds 1.38m), reflecting lower interest rates and capital
expenditure. Gearing fell from 26 per cent to 20 per cent on net borrowings
of Pounds 7m.
Earnings dropped to 21.99p (26.26p). Directors are recommending an improved
final dividend of 7.1p to make a total of 11.5p (11p).
Clifford is converting its Kidlington dairy into an automated carton milk
unit and concentrating all milk bottling at another site.
The changes at Kidlington will involve write-offs and redundancy payments,
the company said. About 30 staff are likely to be laid off.
