FT  26 MAR 92 / Letter: London saved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr OSMAN STREETER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Vanessa Houlder fails to give credit to a justifiable case of post hoc
ergo propter hoc when she writes that 'the cost savings of moving to Canary
Wharf have narrowed over the past two years, as rents in some parts of
central London have halved' (Property Market, March 20). Indeed, they have -
thanks almost entirely to the creation of new office capacity in Docklands.
In the process, London has very possibly been saved from pricing itself out
of the European office rentals markets.
To quote the conclusion of a recent survey: 'London must find a way to
improve its perception of itself and by others more fairly to reflect its
relative strengths.'
Osman Streeter,
Savile Club,
69 Brook Street, London W1
