<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Member control of pensions is urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS would be prevented from using pension fund surpluses for their own
purposes under pensions law proposals being urged by the Institute for
Policy Research, the left-of-centre think tank. It also proposes giving
control over funds to beneficiaries.
The report addresses the most sensitive question being considered by
legislators considering pensions law: whether a pension fund surplus is the
property of the employer or of the scheme's members.
A report by the cross-party Commons social security committee recommended
reform of pension law but declined to examine the question, saying it needed
further study.
The institute report rejects employers' arguments that liability to make
good any deficit entitles them to recoup surpluses. That, the report
concludes, is a 'post-hoc rationalisation of the employer's understandable
wish to control the fund'.
Although employers are correct in theory, the report notes that most scheme
rules give employers the right to cease their contributions at any time,
regardless of the financial state of the pension fund. Provisions in the
1990 Social Security Act will require employers to make good deficiencies
when a pension fund is wound up, but have not yet taken effect.
Even those, the report says, may be ineffective because a financially
troubled employer may simply stop contributing and not wind the fund up
until the options run out - upon bankruptcy. If that happens, there is no
hope of obtaining overdue contributions from the employer.
The report suggests that in return for surrendering their right to use
surpluses built up in pension funds, employers' contributions should be
defined and limited. Employer and employee contributions should be a
contractually binding matter to be renegotiated periodically. Contributions
levels in the event of a surplus or deficit would be spelled out in the
contract.
Meanwhile, making up shortfalls would be a matter to be negotiated between
employers and beneficiaries, by increased contributions from both or
reductions in benefits paid.
The report also dismisses arguments from industry that preventing employers
from securing pension fund surpluses will discourage them from offering
defined benefit schemes.
Locking the Stable Door, Institute of Public Policy Research, 30-32
Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
