<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Scottish recovery remote, study finds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND is escaping the worst effects of the recession, but there is
unlikely to be any real sign of recovery in the Scottish economy in the
first half of this year and very little growth in the year as a whole.
The Fraser of Allander Institute of Strathclyde University, Scotland's main
economic study organisation, which made the forecast in its latest quarterly
bulletin, points out that in January the rate of unemployment north of the
border was indistinguishable from the UK average. That has not happened for
more than a generation.
Whereas unemployment in the UK rose by 62 per cent between March 1990 and
last January, and that in the south-east of England by 128 per cent,
unemployment in Scotland rose by only 13 per cent.
The institute points out that Scotland has been affected much less than
southern Britain by high interest rates, partly because Scots have a lower
level of home ownership and borrowed less in mortgages. Between 1980 and
1989 the ratio of mortgage advances to incomes rose by 19 per cent in
Scotland, compared with a rise of 41 per cent in southern England.
The forecast says the advantages that have protected Scotland from the worst
of recession will unwind as recovery gets under way.
Quarterly Economic Bulletin March 1992, Fraser of Allander Institute, Curran
Building, 100 Cathedral Street, Glasgow G4 0LN. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
