FT  26 MAR 92 / Plan for 24-hour soccer channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FULL TIME Communications, a new company, is planning to set up a
24-hour-a-day satellite television channel dedicated to football. It would
kick off at the start of the 1993-94 season.
It is believed to be the first single-sport subscription television channel
in the world.
The company is offering the English football authorities Pounds 50m a year
for 10 years for the right to broadcast all cup and league games.
The channel would show a mixture of live and recorded games in their
entirety and charge a subscription of about Pounds 10 a month.
Mr Gerald O'Connell, a director of Full Time who also set up Clubcall - the
telephone information service for football clubs - said yesterday that
negotiations with the football authorities were advanced.
Full Time would want some live matches on an exclusive basis, Mr O'Connell
said, but the deal would not preclude the new Premier League, the Football
League or the Football Association dealing with ITV or the BBC.
