<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 92 / Yeltsin faces pressure to step down as premier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICAL pressure is mounting in Moscow to remove Mr Boris Yeltsin as prime
minister and install an administration less committed to radical economic
reform.
Mr Yeltsin, who is both president and prime minister, remains the most
popular Russian politician in the polls, but has been identified with his
government's severe economic reforms and made vulnerable to parliamentary
attack.
The first strong signs of the political offensive against Mr Yeltsin emerged
this week. A meeting on Tuesday of the Constitutional Commission, which is
working on the draft constitution, cut the parliamentary votes needed to
remove a prime minister from two-thirds to a bare majority and deleted Mr
Yeltsin's right to appoint regional governors.
While Mr Yeltsin may be able to restore the clauses he has lost, the victory
of the anti-government forces shows the rising tide of discontent.
The opposition is concentrated among disaffected deputies who are unhappy
with Mr Yeltsin's concentration of powers.
Earlier this month, Mr Yeltsin added the post of defence minister to his
portfolios. Under his presidency, Russia has assumed most of the powers of
the former Soviet Union. In October last year he also won the right in
parliament to legislate by decree - a right deputies now regret.
Mr Yeltsin admitted yesterday that the government would fall if he were
replaced as prime minister, because it is sustained by his own popularity.
No one will challenge him as president, but many Russian deputies feel he
should go as premier.
Many observers believe he will have to sacrifice Mr Genady Burbulis, the
unpopular first deputy prime minister - who received a 0.8 per cent approval
rating in a public opinion poll yesterday - but he may be able to defend Mr
Yegor Gaidar, the deputy prime minister in charge of economic reform.
A senior western diplomat said yesterday: 'Gaidar is very important for the
IMF right now, and Yeltsin knows how important the IMF is to him.' That
said, Mr Gaidar was accused by former presidential advisers on Tuesday of
being a tool in the hands of the Fund.
The opposition, focused on the figures of Mr Alexander Rutskoi, the
vice-president, and more particularly Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the
parliamentary chairman, pits the powers of parliament against those of the
government when the constitution does not clearly define either.
For example, Mr Khasbulatov has 'settled' the threatened airline pilots'
strike by promising to pay them everything they want, though there seems to
have been no liaison between him and the government, which will have to pay
the costs of the settlement.
Mr Gaidar is defending himself strongly, and has banned all talk of
resignation among his team.
G7 aid to Russia, Page 2
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
